# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-formats
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-formats/base64] When comparing the original data to the resulting encoded data, Base64 encoding increases the size by 33% plus about 4% additional if inserting line breaks for typical line length.
[src:data-formats/base64] The earliest uses of this encoding were for dial-up communication between systems running the same operating system – for example, uuencode for UNIX and BinHex for the TRS-80 (later adapted for the Macintosh) – and could therefore make more assumptions about what characters were safe to use.
[src:data-formats/base64] For instance, uuencode uses uppercase letters, digits, and many punctuation characters, but no lowercase.
[src:data-formats/base64] Encoding an attachment as Base64 before sending, and then decoding when received, assures older SMTP servers correctly transmit messages with attached binary information.
[src:data-formats/base64] For example, to include the data of an image in a script to avoid depending on external files.
[src:data-formats/base64] format, some viewers can interpret Base64 when used for embedded elements, such as raster images inside SVG files.
[src:data-formats/base64] can use Base64 to represent file contents.
[src:data-formats/base64] URIs, instead of being supplied in separate files.
[src:data-formats/base64] functionality, especially in cases where the information doesn't warrant being permanently saved or when information must be quickly sent between a wide variety of different, potentially incompatible programs.
[src:data-formats/base64] , which contains binary data, is sometimes stored as Base64 since it is more likely that a QR code reader accurately decodes text than binary data.
[src:data-formats/base64] Also, some devices more readily save text from a QR code than potentially malicious binary data.
[src:data-formats/base64] The set of characters used to represent the values for each base-64 digit (value from 0 to 63) differs slightly between the variations of Base64.
[src:data-formats/base64] The general strategy is to use printable characters that are common to most character encodings.
[src:data-formats/base64] This tends to result in data remaining unchanged as it moves through information systems, such as email, that were traditionally not 8-bit clean.
[src:data-formats/base64] Many variants use `+` and `/` for the last two.
[src:data-formats/base64] Per RFC 4648 §4, the following table lists the characters used for each numeric value.
[src:data-formats/base64] Base64URL encoding replaces `+` with `-` and `/` with `_` to make the encoded string HTTP-safe and avoid the need for escaping.
[src:data-formats/base64] To simplify explanation, the example below uses plain text for input.
[src:data-formats/base64] While this is done in practice, a much more common use is encoding images and other data that are normally not representable with plain text, and the result then represents the data in a printable text format.
[src:data-formats/base64] Each input sequence of 6 bits (which can encode 26 = 64 values) is mapped to a Base64 alphabet letter.
[src:data-formats/base64] Therefore, Base64 encoding results in four characters for each three input bytes.
[src:data-formats/base64] Which encodes the string `TWFu` (per ASCII or similar).
[src:data-formats/base64] The following table shows how input is encoded.
[src:data-formats/base64] For example, the letter 'M' has the value `77` (per ASCII and similar).
[src:data-formats/base64] The first 6 bits of the value is `010011` or 19 decimal which maps to Base64 letter 'T' which has a value `84` (per ASCII and similar).
[src:data-formats/base64] If the input consists of a number of bytes that is 2 more than a multiple of 3 (e.g.
[src:data-formats/base64] 'M', 'a'), then the last 2 bytes (16 bits) are encoded in 3 Base64 digits (18 bits).
[src:data-formats/base64] The two least significant bits of the last content-bearing 6-bit block are treated as zero for encoding and discarded for decoding (along with the trailing `=` padding character).
[src:data-formats/base64] If the input consists of a number of bytes that is 1 more than a multiple of 3 (e.g.
[src:data-formats/base64] 'M'), then the last 8 bits are represented in 2 Base64 digits (12 bits).
[src:data-formats/base64] When decoding, each sequence of four encoded characters is converted to three output bytes, but with a single padding character the final 4 characters decode to only two bytes, or with two padding characters, the final 4 characters decode to a single byte.
[src:data-formats/base64] Another way to interpret the padding character is to consider it as an instruction to discard 2 trailing bits from the bit string each time a `=` is encountered.
[src:data-formats/base64] For example, when bGlnaHQgdw== is decoded, we convert each character (except the trailing occurrences of `=`) into their corresponding 6-bit representation, and then discard 2 trailing bits for the first `=` and another 2 trailing bits for the other `=`.
[src:data-formats/base64] In this instance, we would get 6 bits from the `d`, and another 6 bits from the `w` for a bit string of length 12, but since we remove 2 bits for each `=` (for a total of 4 bits), the `dw==` ends up producing 8 bits (1 byte) when decoded.
[src:data-formats/base64] Use of the padding character in encoded text is not essential for decoding.
[src:data-formats/base64] The number of missing bytes can be inferred from the length of the encoded text.
[src:data-formats/base64] In some variants, the padding character is mandatory, while for others it is not used.
[src:data-formats/base64] Notably, when concatenating Base64 encoded strings, then use of padding characters is *required* during encoding to avoid ambiguity when decoding.
[src:data-formats/base64] Without padding, after decoding each sequence of 4 encoded characters, there may be 2 or 3 encoded characters left over.
[src:data-formats/base64] A single remaining encoded character is not possible because a single Base64 character only contains 6 bits, and 8 bits are required to create a byte.
[src:data-formats/base64] The first Base64 character contributes 6 bits, and the second Base64 character contributes its first 2 bits to finish filling the byte.
[src:data-formats/base64] The following table demonstrates decoding encoded strings that have 2, 3 or no left-over characters.
[src:data-formats/base64] Decoding without padding is not performed consistently among decoders - some decoders require padding while other decoders infer the correct amount of padding from the encoded input string.
[src:data-formats/base64] In addition, allowing padless decoding by definition allows one list of strings written in some particular order to decode into several possible different output strings rather than only one possible output string, which can be a security risk due to the unpredictable and/or unexpected decoding.
[src:data-formats/base64] Variations of Base64 differ in the alphabet used and structural aspects like maximum line length.
[src:data-formats/base64] The most commonly used alphabet is that described by RFC 4648 and most variations only differ in the last two letters used.
[src:data-formats/base64] The following table describes more commonly used encodings that are specified by an RFC.
[src:data-formats/base64] RFC 4648 describes a various encodings including Base64, and it discusses the use of line feeds in encoded data, the use of padding in encoded data, the use of non-alphabet characters in encoded data, use of different encoding alphabets, and canonical encodings.
[src:data-formats/base64] The variant that it calls *Base 64 Encoding* and *base64* is intended for general-use.
[src:data-formats/base64] The RFC also specifies a second Base64 encoding that it calls *Base 64 Encoding with URL and Filename Safe Alphabet* that is intended for representing relatively long identifying information.
[src:data-formats/base64] For example, a database persistence framework for Java objects might use Base64 encoding to encode a relatively large unique id (generally 128-bit UUIDs) as a string for use as an HTTP parameter in an HTTP form or an HTTP GET URL.
[src:data-formats/base64] Also, many applications need to encode binary data in a way that is convenient for inclusion in a URL, including in hidden web form fields, and Base64 is a convenient encoding to render them in a compact way.
[src:data-formats/base64] Using standard Base64 in a URL requires encoding the `+`, `/` and `=` characters as special percent-encoded hexadecimal sequences (`+` becomes `%2B`, `/` becomes `%2F` and `=` becomes `%3D`), which makes the string longer and harder to read.
[src:data-formats/base64] Using a different alphabet allows for encoding as Base64 without requiring this extra markup.
[src:data-formats/base64] Typically, `+` and `/` are replaced by `-` and `_`, respectively, so that using URL encoders/decoders is no longer necessary and has no effect on the length of the encoded value, leaving the same encoded form intact for use in relational databases, web forms, and object identifiers in general.
[src:data-formats/base64] A popular site to make use of such is YouTube.
[src:data-formats/base64] Some variants allow or require omitting the padding `=` signs to avoid them being confused with field separators, or require that any such padding be percent-encoded.
[src:data-formats/base64] Some libraries encode `=` as `.`, potentially exposing applications to relative path attacks when a folder name is encoded from user data.
[src:data-formats/base64] RFC 3548, entitled *The Base16, Base32, and Base64 Data Encodings*, is an informational (non-normative) memo that attempts to unify the RFC 1421 and RFC 2045 specifications of Base64 encodings, alternative-alphabet encodings, and the Base32 (which is seldom used) and Base16 encodings.
[src:data-formats/base64] The MIME (Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions) specification lists Base64 as one of two binary-to-text encoding schemes (the other being quoted-printable).
[src:data-formats/base64] MIME's Base64 encoding is based on that of the RFC 1421 version of PEM: it uses the same 64-character alphabet and encoding mechanism as PEM and uses the `=` symbol for output padding in the same way, as described at RFC 2045.
[src:data-formats/base64] MIME does not specify a fixed length for Base64-encoded lines, but it does specify a maximum line length of 76 characters.
[src:data-formats/base64] Additionally, it specifies that any character outside the standard set of 64 encoding characters (for example CRLF sequences), must be ignored by a compliant decoder, although most implementations use a CR/LF newline pair to delimit encoded lines.
[src:data-formats/base64] Thus, the actual length of MIME-compliant Base64-encoded binary data is usually about 137% of the original data length (4⁄3×78⁄76), though for very short messages the overhead can be much higher due to the overhead of the headers.
[src:data-formats/base64] Very roughly, the final size of Base64-encoded binary data is equal to 1.37 times the original data size + 814 bytes (for headers).
[src:data-formats/base64] The first known standardized use of the encoding now called MIME Base64 was in the Privacy-Enhanced Mail (PEM) protocol, proposed by RFC 989 in 1987.
[src:data-formats/base64] PEM defines a "printable encoding" scheme that uses Base64 encoding to transform an arbitrary sequence of bytes to a format that can be expressed in short lines of 6-bit characters, as required by transfer protocols such as SMTP.
[src:data-formats/base64] The current version of PEM (specified in RFC 1421) uses a 64-character alphabet consisting of upper- and lower-case Roman letters (`A`–`Z`, `a`–`z`), the numerals (`0`–`9`), and the `+` and `/` symbols.
[src:data-formats/base64] The `=` symbol is also used as a padding suffix.
[src:data-formats/base64] The original specification, RFC 989, additionally used the `*` symbol to delimit encoded but unencrypted data within the output stream.
[src:data-formats/base64] To convert data to PEM printable encoding, the first byte is placed in the most significant eight bits of a 24-bit buffer, the next in the middle eight, and the third in the least significant eight bits.
[src:data-formats/base64] If there are fewer than three bytes left to encode (or in total), the remaining buffer bits will be zero.
[src:data-formats/base64] The buffer is then used, six bits at a time, most significant first, as indices into the string: "`ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789+/`", and the indicated character is output.
[src:data-formats/base64] The process is repeated on the remaining data until fewer than four bytes remain.
[src:data-formats/base64] If three bytes remain, they are processed normally.
[src:data-formats/base64] If fewer than three bytes (24 bits) are remaining to encode, the input data is right-padded with zero bits to form an integral multiple of six bits.
[src:data-formats/base64] After encoding the non-padded data, if two bytes of the 24-bit buffer are padded-zeros, two `=` characters are appended to the output; if one byte of the 24-bit buffer is filled with padded-zeros, one `=` character is appended.
[src:data-formats/base64] This signals the decoder that the zero bits added due to padding should be excluded from the reconstructed data.
[src:data-formats/base64] This also guarantees that the encoded output length is a multiple of 4 bytes.
[src:data-formats/base64] PEM requires that all encoded lines consist of exactly 64 printable characters, with the exception of the last line, which may contain fewer printable characters.
[src:data-formats/base64] Lines are delimited by whitespace characters according to local (platform-specific) conventions.
[src:data-formats/base64] UTF-7, described first in RFC 1642, which was later superseded by RFC 2152, introduced a system called *modified Base64*.
[src:data-formats/base64] This data encoding scheme is used to encode UTF-16 as ASCII characters for use in 7-bit transports such as SMTP.
[src:data-formats/base64] It is a variant of the Base64 encoding used in MIME.
[src:data-formats/base64] The "Modified Base64" alphabet consists of the MIME Base64 alphabet, but does not use the "`=`" padding character.
[src:data-formats/base64] UTF-7 is intended for use in mail headers (defined in RFC 2047), and the "`=`" character is reserved in that context as the escape character for "quoted-printable" encoding.
[src:data-formats/base64] Modified Base64 simply omits the padding and ends immediately after the last Base64 digit containing useful bits leaving up to three unused bits in the last Base64 digit.
[src:data-formats/base64] OpenPGP, described in RFC 9580, specifies "ASCII armor", which is identical to the "Base64" encoding described by MIME, with the addition of an optional 24-bit CRC.
[src:data-formats/base64] The checksum is calculated on the input data before encoding; the checksum is then encoded with the same Base64 algorithm and, prefixed by the "`=`" symbol as the separator, appended to the encoded output data.
[src:data-formats/base64] The `atob()` and `btoa()` JavaScript methods, defined in the HTML5 draft specification, provide Base64 encoding and decoding functionality to web pages.
[src:data-formats/base64] The `btoa()` method outputs padding characters, but these are optional in the input of the `atob()` method.
[src:data-formats/base64] Example: Encoding of the beginning of a GIF file: `btoa("GIF89a")` ↦ `"R0lGODlh"`.
[src:data-formats/base64] Several variants use alphabets similar to the common variants, but in a different order.
[src:data-formats/base64] An advantage over RFC 4648 is that sorting encoded ASCII data results in the same order as sorting the plain ASCII data.
[src:data-formats/base64] 5.5 standard for genealogical data interchange encodes multimedia files in its text-line hierarchical file format.
[src:data-formats/base64] Some variants use a Base64 alphabet that is significantly different from the alphabets used in the most common Base64 variants (like RFC 4648).
[src:data-formats/base64] Avoiding all lower-case letters was helpful, because many older printers only printed uppercase.
[src:data-formats/base64] Using consecutive ASCII characters saved computing power, because it was only necessary to add 32, without requiring a lookup table.
[src:data-formats/base64] Its use of most punctuation characters and the space character may limit its usefulness in some applications, such as those that use these characters as syntax.
[src:data-formats/base64] Its alphabet includes additional punctuation characters.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] CSV is not limited to a particular character encoding but should be and is commonly used with UTF-8, particularly because it does not provide a way to indicate the character encoding.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] The CSV format predates personal computers by more than a decade.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] The IBM Fortran (level H extended) compiler under OS/360 supported list-directed ("free-form") input/output, with commas between values, in 1972.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] List-directed input/output was defined in FORTRAN 77, approved in 1978.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] List-directed input used commas or spaces for delimiters, so unquoted character strings could not contain commas or spaces.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] The term "comma-separated value" and the "CSV" abbreviation were in use by 1983.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] The manual for the Osborne Executive computer, which bundled the SuperCalc spreadsheet, documents the CSV quoting convention that allows strings to contain embedded commas.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Comma-separated value lists are easier to type (for example into punched cards) than fixed-column-aligned data, and they were less prone to producing incorrect results if a value was punched one column off from its intended location.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Comma separated files are used for the interchange of database information between machines of two different architectures.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] The plain-text character of CSV files largely avoids incompatibilities such as byte-order and word size.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] The files are largely human-readable, so it is easier to deal with them in the absence of perfect documentation or communication.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] The main standardization initiative—transforming "*de facto* fuzzy definition" into a more precise and *de jure* one—was in 2005, with RFC 4180, defining CSV as a MIME Content Type.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Later, in 2013, some of RFC 4180's deficiencies were tackled by a W3C recommendation.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] In 2014 IETF published RFC 7111 describing the application of URI fragments to CSV documents.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] RFC 7111 specifies how row, column, and cell ranges can be selected from a CSV document using position indexes.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] In 2015 W3C, in an attempt to enhance CSV with formal semantics, publicized the first *drafts of recommendations* for CSV metadata standards, which began as *recommendations* in December of the same year.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] CSV can be informally described as plain text data consisting of one record per line, where each line has the same sequence of fields separated by a comma.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] The format is more formally described in the 2005 technical standard RFC 4180 which codifies the CSV format and defines the MIME type `text/csv` for the handling of text-based fields.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] This example illustrates that a CSV cannot be parsed by naïvely splitting the data by line terminators into lines, and then each line by commas.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] In 2011, Open Knowledge Foundation (OKF) and various partners created a data protocols working group, which later evolved into the Frictionless Data initiative.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] One of the main formats they released was the Tabular Data Package.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Tabular Data package was heavily based on CSV, using it as the main data transport format and adding basic type and schema metadata.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] (CSV lacks any type information to distinguish the string `1` from the number 1.) The Frictionless Data Initiative has also provided a standard CSV Dialect Description Format for describing different dialects of CSV, for example specifying the field separator or quoting rules.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] In 2013, the W3C "CSV on the Web" working group began to specify technologies providing higher interoperability for web applications using CSV or similar formats.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] The working group completed its work in February 2016 and is officially closed in March 2016 with the release of a set of documents and W3C recommendations for modeling "Tabular Data", and enhancing CSV with metadata and semantics.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] While the well-formedness of CSV data can readily be checked, testing validity and canonical form is less well developed, relative to more precise data formats, such as XML and SQL, which offer richer types and rules-based validation.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] CSV is commonly used for data exchange and is widely supported by data-oriented applications.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] It is often used to move tabular data between programs that natively operate on incompatible data – often in formats that are proprietary or undocumented.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] A common scenario is moving data from a database to a spreadsheet which, in general, use completely different formats.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Most database systems can export as CSV and most spreadsheet programs can import CSV-formatted data, leveraging CSV as an intermediate format.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Every major ecommerce platform provides support for exporting data as a CSV file.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Common data science tools such as Pandas include the option to export data to CSV for long-term storage.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Benefits of CSV for data storage include the simplicity of CSV makes parsing and creating CSV files easy to implement and fast compared to other data formats, human readability making editing or fixing data simpler, and high compressibility leading to smaller data files.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Alternatively, CSV does not support more complex data relations and makes no distinction between null and empty values, and in applications where these features are needed other formats are preferred.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] More than 200 local, regional, and national data portals, such as those of the UK government and the European Commission, use CSV files with standardized data catalogs.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Some applications use CSV as a data interchange format to enhance its interoperability, exporting and importing CSV.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] CSV is supported by almost all spreadsheets and database management systems.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Spreadsheets including Apple Numbers, LibreOffice Calc, and Apache OpenOffice Calc. support reading CSV files.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Microsoft Excel also supports a dialect of CSV with restrictions in comparison to other spreadsheet software (e.g., as of 2019 Excel still cannot export CSV files in the commonly used UTF-8 character encoding, and separator is not enforced to be the comma).
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] LibreOffice Calc CSV importer is actually a more generic delimited text importer, supporting multiple separators at the same time as well as field trimming.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Various relational databases support saving query results to a CSV file.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] PostgreSQL provides the `COPY` command, which allows for both saving and loading data to and from a file.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] `COPY (SELECT * FROM articles) TO '/home/wikipedia/file.csv' (FORMAT csv)` saves the content of a table `articles` to a file called `/home/wikipedia/file.csv`.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Some relational databases, when using standard SQL, offer *foreign-data wrapper* (FDW).
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] For example, PostgreSQL offers the `CREATE FOREIGN TABLE` and `CREATE EXTENSION file_fdw` commands to configure any variant of CSV.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Databases like Apache Hive offer the option to express CSV or .csv.gz as an internal table format.
[src:data-formats/comma-separated-values] Programs that work with CSV may have limits on the maximum number of rows CSV files can have.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:data-formats/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:data-formats/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:data-formats/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:data-formats/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:data-formats/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:data-formats/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:data-formats/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:data-formats/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:data-formats/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:data-formats/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:data-formats/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:data-formats/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:data-formats/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:data-formats/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:data-formats/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:data-formats/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:data-formats/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:data-formats/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:data-formats/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:data-formats/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:data-formats/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:data-formats/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:data-formats/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:data-formats/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:data-formats/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:data-formats/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:data-formats/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:data-formats/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:data-formats/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:data-formats/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:data-formats/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:data-formats/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:data-formats/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:data-formats/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:data-formats/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:data-formats/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:data-formats/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:data-formats/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:data-formats/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:data-formats/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:data-formats/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:data-formats/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:data-formats/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:data-formats/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:data-formats/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:data-formats/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:data-formats/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:data-formats/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:data-formats/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:data-formats/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:data-formats/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:data-formats/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:data-formats/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:data-formats/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:data-formats/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:data-formats/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:data-formats/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:data-formats/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:data-formats/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:data-formats/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:data-formats/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:data-formats/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:data-formats/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:data-formats/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:data-formats/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:data-formats/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:data-formats/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:data-formats/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:data-formats/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:data-formats/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:data-formats/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:data-formats/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:data-formats/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:data-formats/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:data-formats/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:data-formats/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:data-formats/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:data-formats/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:data-formats/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:data-formats/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:data-formats/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:data-formats/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:data-formats/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:data-formats/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:data-formats/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:data-formats/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:data-formats/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:data-formats/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:data-formats/markdown] The initial description of Markdown contained ambiguities and raised unanswered questions, causing implementations to both intentionally and accidentally diverge from the original version.
[src:data-formats/markdown] This was addressed in 2014 when long-standing Markdown contributors released CommonMark, an unambiguous specification and test suite for Markdown.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Markdown was inspired by pre-existing conventions for marking up plain text in email and usenet posts, such as the earlier markup languages setext (c.
[src:data-formats/markdown] In 2002, Aaron Swartz created atx and referred to it as "the true structured text format".
[src:data-formats/markdown] Gruber created the Markdown language in 2004 with Swartz as his "sounding board".
[src:data-formats/markdown] The goal of the language was to enable people "to write using an easy-to-read and easy-to-write plain text format, optionally convert it to structurally valid XHTML (or HTML)".
[src:data-formats/markdown] Gruber wrote a Perl script, `Markdown.pl`, which converts marked-up text input to valid, well-formed XHTML or HTML, encoding angle brackets (`<`, `>`) and ampersands (`&`), which would be misinterpreted as special characters in those languages.
[src:data-formats/markdown] It can take the role of a standalone script, a plugin for Blosxom or Movable Type, or of a text filter for BBEdit.
[src:data-formats/markdown] As Markdown's popularity grew rapidly, many Markdown implementations appeared, driven mostly by the need for additional features such as tables, footnotes, definition lists, and Markdown inside HTML blocks.
[src:data-formats/markdown] The behavior of some of these diverged from the reference implementation, as Markdown was only characterised by an informal specification and a Perl implementation for conversion to HTML.
[src:data-formats/markdown] At the same time, a number of ambiguities in the informal specification had attracted attention.
[src:data-formats/markdown] These issues spurred the creation of tools such as Babelmark to compare the output of various implementations, and an effort by some developers of Markdown parsers for standardization.
[src:data-formats/markdown] However, Gruber has argued that complete standardization would be a mistake: "Different sites (and people) have different needs.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Gruber avoided using curly braces in Markdown to unofficially reserve them for implementation-specific extensions.
[src:data-formats/markdown] In 2012, a group of people, including Jeff Atwood and John MacFarlane, launched what Atwood characterised as a standardization effort.
[src:data-formats/markdown] A community website now aims to "document various tools and resources available to document authors and developers, as well as implementors of the various Markdown implementations".
[src:data-formats/markdown] In September 2014, Gruber objected to the usage of "Markdown" in the name of this effort and it was rebranded as "CommonMark".
[src:data-formats/markdown] CommonMark.org published several versions of a specification, reference implementation, test suite, and "[plans] to announce a finalized 1.0 spec and test suite in 2019".
[src:data-formats/markdown] A finalized 1.0 spec has not been released, as major issues still remain unsolved.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Nonetheless, several websites and projects have adopted CommonMark, including Codeberg, Discourse, GitHub, GitLab, Reddit, Qt, Stack Exchange (Stack Overflow), and Swift.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Websites like Bitbucket, Diaspora, Discord, GitHub, OpenStreetMap, Reddit, SourceForge and Stack Exchange use variants of Markdown to make discussions between users easier.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Depending on implementation, basic inline HTML tags may be supported.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Italic text may be implemented by `_underscores_` or `*single-asterisks*`.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Many platforms implement spoiler formatting that hides text until hovered, clicked or tapped.
[src:data-formats/markdown] The most common markup is ||spoiler|| used by Discord, Telegram, various Matrix clients, now defunct Guilded, a forum called Flarum, a NodeBB plugin, the imageboard engine JSChan and possibly more.
[src:data-formats/markdown] GitHub had been using its own variant of Markdown since as early as 2009, which added support for additional formatting such as tables and nesting block content inside list elements, as well as GitHub-specific features such as auto-linking references to commits, issues, usernames, etc.
[src:data-formats/markdown] In 2017, GitHub released a formal specification of its GitHub Flavored Markdown (GFM) that is based on CommonMark.
[src:data-formats/markdown] It is a strict superset of CommonMark, following its specification exactly except for tables, strikethrough, autolinks and task lists, which GFM adds as extensions.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Accordingly, GitHub also changed the parser used on their sites, which required that some documents be changed.
[src:data-formats/markdown] For instance, GFM now requires that the hash symbol that creates a heading be separated from the heading text by a space character.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Markdown Extra is a lightweight markup language based on Markdown implemented in PHP (originally), Python and Ruby.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Markdown Extra is supported in some content management systems such as Drupal, Grav (CMS), Textpattern CMS and TYPO3.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Implementations of Markdown are available for over a dozen programming languages; in addition, many applications, platforms and frameworks support Markdown.
[src:data-formats/markdown] For example, Markdown plugins exist for every major blogging platform.
[src:data-formats/markdown] While Markdown is a minimal markup language and is read and edited with a normal text editor, there are specially designed editors that preview the files with styles, which are available for all major platforms.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Many general-purpose text and code editors have syntax highlighting plugins for Markdown built into them or available as optional download.
[src:data-formats/markdown] Editors may feature a side-by-side preview window or render the code directly in a WYSIWYG fashion.
[src:data-formats/toml] Among other constructs, TOML's syntax primarily consists of key-value pairs, section names in square brackets, and comments delimited by a leading `#`.
[src:data-formats/toml] TOML's syntax is a superset of the INI format.
[src:data-formats/toml] Contrary to the INI format, which comprises multiple competing variants as a result of ad-hoc parsers, TOML has a formally agreed-upon syntax.
[src:data-formats/toml] TOML supports the following data types: string, integer, float, boolean, datetime, array, and table.
[src:data-formats/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:data-formats/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:data-formats/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:data-formats/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:data-formats/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:data-formats/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:data-formats/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:data-formats/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:data-formats/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:data-formats/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:data-formats/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:data-formats/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:data-formats/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:data-formats/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:data-formats/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:data-formats/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:data-formats/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:data-formats/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:data-formats/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:data-formats/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:data-formats/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:data-formats/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:data-formats/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:data-formats/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:data-formats/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:data-formats/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:data-formats/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:data-formats/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:data-formats/xml] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:data-formats/xml] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:data-formats/xml] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:data-formats/xml] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:data-formats/xml] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:data-formats/xml] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:data-formats/xml] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:data-formats/xml] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:data-formats/xml] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:data-formats/xml] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:data-formats/xml] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:data-formats/xml] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:data-formats/xml] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:data-formats/xml] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:data-formats/xml] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:data-formats/xml] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:data-formats/xml] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:data-formats/xml] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:data-formats/xml] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:data-formats/xml] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:data-formats/xml] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:data-formats/xml] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:data-formats/xml] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:data-formats/xml] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:data-formats/xml] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:data-formats/xml] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:data-formats/xml] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:data-formats/xml] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:data-formats/xml] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:data-formats/xml] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:data-formats/xml] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:data-formats/xml] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:data-formats/xml] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:data-formats/xml] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:data-formats/xml] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:data-formats/xml] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:data-formats/xml] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:data-formats/xml] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:data-formats/xml] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:data-formats/xml] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:data-formats/xml] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:data-formats/xml] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:data-formats/xml] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:data-formats/xml] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:data-formats/xml] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:data-formats/xml] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:data-formats/xml] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:data-formats/xml] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:data-formats/xml] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:data-formats/xml] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:data-formats/xml] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:data-formats/xml] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:data-formats/xml] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:data-formats/xml] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:data-formats/xml] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:data-formats/xml] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:data-formats/xml] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:data-formats/xml] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:data-formats/xml] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:data-formats/xml] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:data-formats/xml] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:data-formats/xml] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:data-formats/xml] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:data-formats/xml] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:data-formats/xml] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:data-formats/xml] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:data-formats/xml] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:data-formats/xml] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:data-formats/xml] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:data-formats/xml] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:data-formats/xml] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:data-formats/xml] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:data-formats/xml] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:data-formats/xml] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:data-formats/xml] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:data-formats/xml] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:data-formats/xml] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:data-formats/xml] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:data-formats/xml] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:data-formats/xml] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:data-formats/xml] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:data-formats/xml] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:data-formats/xml] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:data-formats/xml] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:data-formats/xml] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:data-formats/xml] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:data-formats/xml] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:data-formats/xml] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:data-formats/xml] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:data-formats/xml] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:data-formats/xml] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:data-formats/xml] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:data-formats/xml] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:data-formats/xml] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:data-formats/xml] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:data-formats/xml] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:data-formats/xml] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:data-formats/xml] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:data-formats/xml] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:data-formats/xml] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:data-formats/xml] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:data-formats/xml] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:data-formats/xml] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:data-formats/xml] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:data-formats/xml] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:data-formats/xml] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Custom data types are allowed, but YAML natively encodes scalars (such as strings, integers, and floats), lists, and associative arrays (also known as maps, dictionaries or hashmaps).
[src:data-formats/yaml] These data types are based on the Perl programming language, though all commonly used high-level programming languages share very similar concepts.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The colon-centered syntax, used for expressing key-value pairs, is inspired by electronic mail headers as defined in RFC 822, and the document separator `---` is borrowed from MIME (RFC 2046).
[src:data-formats/yaml] Escape sequences are reused from C, and whitespace wrapping for multi-line strings is inspired by HTML.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Lists and hashes can contain nested lists and hashes, forming a tree structure; arbitrary graphs can be represented using YAML aliases (similar to XML in SOAP).
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML is intended to be read and written in streams, a feature inspired by SAX.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Support for reading and writing YAML is available for many programming languages.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Some source-code editors such as Vim, Emacs, and various integrated development environments have features that make editing YAML easier, such as folding up nested structures or automatically highlighting syntax errors.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The official recommended filename extension for YAML files has been `.yaml` since 2006.
[src:data-formats/yaml] In 2024, the MIME type `application/yaml` has been finalized.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML (/ˈjæməl/, rhymes with *camel*) was first proposed by Clark Evans in 2001, who designed it together with Ingy döt Net and Oren Ben-Kiki.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Originally YAML was said to mean *Yet Another Markup Language*, because it was released in an era that saw a proliferation of markup languages for presentation and connectivity (HTML, XML, SGML, etc.).
[src:data-formats/yaml] A cheat sheet and full specification are available at the official site.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The following is a synopsis of the basic elements.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML accepts the entire Unicode character set, except for some control characters, and may be encoded in any one of UTF-8, UTF-16 or UTF-32.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Conventional block format uses a hyphen+space to begin a new item in list.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Optional inline format is delimited by comma+space and enclosed in brackets (similar to JSON).
[src:data-formats/yaml] Keys are separated from values by a colon+space.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Indented blocks, common in YAML data files, use indentation and new lines to separate the key/value pairs.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Inline blocks, common in YAML data streams, use comma+space to separate the key/value pairs between braces.
[src:data-formats/yaml] There are two ways to write multi-line strings, one preserving newlines (using the `|` character) and one that folds the newlines (using the `>` character), both followed by a newline character.
[src:data-formats/yaml] By default, the leading indentation (of the first line) and trailing whitespace are stripped, though other behavior can be explicitly specified.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Folded text converts newlines to spaces and removes leading whitespace.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Objects and lists are important components in yaml and can be mixed.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The first example is a list of key-value objects, all people from the Smith family.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The second lists them by gender; it is a key-value object containing two lists.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Features that distinguish YAML from the capabilities of other data-serialization languages are structures, and data and composite keys.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML structures enable storage of multiple documents within a single file, usage of references for repeated nodes, and usage of arbitrary nodes as keys.
[src:data-formats/yaml] For clarity, compactness, and avoiding data entry errors, YAML provides node anchors (using `&`) and references (using `*`).
[src:data-formats/yaml] References to the anchor work for all data types (see the ship-to reference in the example below).
[src:data-formats/yaml] Below is an example of a queue in an instrument sequencer in which two steps are referenced without being fully described.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Explicit data typing is seldom seen in the majority of YAML documents since YAML autodetects simple types.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Data types can be divided into three categories: core, defined, and user-defined.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Core are ones expected to exist in any parser (e.g. floats, ints, strings, lists, maps, ...).
[src:data-formats/yaml] Many more advanced data types, such as binary data, are defined in the YAML specification but not supported in all implementations.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Finally YAML defines a way to extend the data type definitions locally to accommodate user-defined classes, structures or primitives (e.g. quad-precision floats).
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML autodetects the datatype of the entity, but sometimes one wants to cast the datatype explicitly.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The most common situation is where a single-word string that looks like a number, Boolean or tag requires disambiguation by surrounding it with quotes or using an explicit datatype tag.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Not every implementation of YAML has every specification-defined data type.
[src:data-formats/yaml] These built-in types use a double-exclamation sigil prefix (`!!`).
[src:data-formats/yaml] Particularly interesting ones not shown here are sets, ordered maps, timestamps, and hexadecimal.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Here is an example of base64-encoded binary data.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Many implementations of YAML can support user-defined data types for object serialization.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Local data types are not universal data types but are defined in the application using the YAML parser library.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Local data types use a single exclamation mark (`!`).
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML supports composite keys, which consist of multiple values.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Such keys are useful for coordinate transformations, multi-field identifiers, test cases with compound conditions, and the like.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Data-structure hierarchy is maintained by outline indentation.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Notice that strings do not require enclosure in quotation marks.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The specific number of spaces in the indentation is unimportant as long as parallel elements have the same left justification and the hierarchically nested elements are indented further.
[src:data-formats/yaml] This sample document defines an associative array with 7 top level keys: one of the keys, "items", contains a 2-element list, each element of which is itself an associative array with differing keys.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Relational data and redundancy removal are displayed: the "ship-to" associative array content is copied from the "bill-to" associative array's content as indicated by the anchor (`&`) and reference (`*`) labels.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Optional blank lines can be added for readability.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Multiple documents can exist in a single file/stream and are separated by `---`.
[src:data-formats/yaml] An optional `...` can be used at the end of a file (useful for signaling an end in streamed communications without closing the pipe).
[src:data-formats/yaml] Because YAML primarily relies on outline indentation for structure, it is especially resistant to delimiter collision.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML may be placed in JSON by quoting and escaping all interior quotation marks.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML may be placed in XML by escaping reserved characters (`<`, `>`, `&`, `'`, `"`) and converting whitespace, or by placing it in a CDATA section.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Unlike JSON, which can only represent data in a hierarchical model with each child node having a single parent, YAML also offers a simple relational scheme that allows repeats of identical data to be referenced from two or more points in the tree rather than entered redundantly at those points.
[src:data-formats/yaml] This is similar to the facility IDREF built into XML.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The YAML parser then expands these references into the fully populated data structures they imply when read in, so whatever program is using the parser does not have to be aware of a relational encoding model, unlike XML processors, which do not expand references.
[src:data-formats/yaml] This expansion can enhance readability while reducing data entry errors in configuration files or processing protocols where many parameters remain the same in a sequential series of records while only a few vary.
[src:data-formats/yaml] An example being that "ship-to" and "bill-to" records in an invoice are nearly always the same data.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML is purely a data-representation language and thus has no executable commands.
[src:data-formats/yaml] While validation and safe parsing is inherently possible in any data language, implementation is such a notorious pitfall that YAML's lack of an associated command language may be a relative security benefit.
[src:data-formats/yaml] However, YAML allows language-specific tags so that arbitrary local objects can be created by a parser that supports those tags.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Any YAML parser that allows sophisticated object instantiation to be executed opens the potential for an injection attack.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Perl parsers that allow loading of objects of arbitrary classes create so-called "blessed" values.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Using these values may trigger unexpected behavior, e.g. if the class uses overloaded operators.
[src:data-formats/yaml] This may lead to execution of arbitrary Perl code.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The situation is similar for Python or Ruby parsers.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The YAML specification identifies an *instance document* as a "Presentation" or "character stream".
[src:data-formats/yaml] The primary logical structures in a YAML instance document are scalars, sequences, and mappings.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The YAML specification also indicates some basic constraints that apply to these primary logical structures.
[src:data-formats/yaml] For example, according to the specification, mapping keys do not have an order.
[src:data-formats/yaml] In every case where node order is significant, a sequence must be used.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Moreover, in defining conformance for YAML processors, the YAML specification defines two primary operations: *dump* and *load*.
[src:data-formats/yaml] All YAML-compliant processors must provide *at least* one of these operations, and may optionally provide both.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Finally, the YAML specification defines an *information model* or "representation graph", which must be created during processing for both *dump* and *load* operations, although this representation need not be made available to the user through an API.
[src:data-formats/yaml] JSON syntax is a basis of YAML version 1.2, which was promulgated with the express purpose of bringing YAML "into compliance with JSON as an official subset".
[src:data-formats/yaml] Though prior versions of YAML were not strictly compatible, the discrepancies were rarely noticeable, and most JSON documents can be parsed by some YAML parsers such as Syck.
[src:data-formats/yaml] This is because JSON's semantic structure is equivalent to the optional "inline-style" of writing YAML.
[src:data-formats/yaml] While extended hierarchies can be written in inline-style like JSON, this is not a recommended YAML style except when it aids clarity.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML has many additional features not present in JSON, including comments, extensible data types, relational anchors, strings without quotation marks, and mapping types preserving key order.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Due to the conciseness, JSON serialization and deserialization is much faster than YAML.
[src:data-formats/yaml] TOML was designed to be an advancement of the .ini file format.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML makes minimal use of indicator characters compared to TOML's strict requirement of quotation marks and square brackets.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML's use of significant indentation has been contrasted with the dot notation of TOML's key and table names to convey the same semantic structure.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Opinions differ on which convention leads to more-readable configuration files.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML lacks the notion of tag attributes that are found in XML.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Instead YAML has extensible type declarations (including class types for objects).
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML itself does not have XML's language-defined document schema descriptors that allow, for example, a document to self-validate.
[src:data-formats/yaml] However, there are several externally defined schema descriptor languages for YAML (e.g.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Doctrine, Kwalify and Rx) that fulfill that role.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Moreover, the semantics provided by YAML's language-defined type declarations in the YAML document itself frequently relaxes the need for a validator in simple, common situations.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Additionally, YAXML, which represents YAML data structures in XML, allows XML schema importers and output mechanisms like XSLT to be applied to YAML.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Comparison of data-serialization formats provides a more comprehensive comparison of YAML with other serialization formats.
[src:data-formats/yaml] For fixed data structures, YAML files can simply be generated using *print* commands that write both the data and the YAML specific decoration.
[src:data-formats/yaml] To dump varying, or complex, hierarchical data, however, a dedicated YAML *emitter* is preferable.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Similarly, simple YAML files (e.g. key-value pairs) are readily parsed with regular expressions.
[src:data-formats/yaml] For more complex, or varying, data structures, a formal YAML *parser* is recommended.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML emitters and parsers exist for many popular languages.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Most of them are written in the native language itself.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Some are language bindings of the C library *libyaml*; they may run faster.
[src:data-formats/yaml] There used to be another C library, called *Syck*, written and orphaned by why the lucky stiff: it is unmaintained, there is no authoritative source bundle, and the web site has been hijacked.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Hence the only recommendable C library is *libyaml*.
[src:data-formats/yaml] It was originally developed by Kirill Simonov.
[src:data-formats/yaml] In 2018, development was resumed by the new maintainers Ian Cordasco and Ingy döt Net.
[src:data-formats/yaml] C++ programmers have the choice between the C library *libyaml* and the C++ library *libyaml-cpp*.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Both have completely independent code bases and completely different APIs.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The library *libyaml-cpp* still has a major version number of 0, indicating that the API may change at any moment, as happened indeed after version 0.3.
[src:data-formats/yaml] There is a grammar-focused implementation written in C#, with an aim on extensions for the nested elements.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Some implementations of YAML, such as Perl's YAML.pm, will load an entire file (stream) and parse it *en masse*.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Other implementations like PyYaml are lazy and iterate over the next document only upon request.
[src:data-formats/yaml] For very large files in which one plans to handle the documents independently, instantiating the entire file before processing may be prohibitive.
[src:data-formats/yaml] Thus in YAML.pm, occasionally one must chunk a file into documents and parse those individually.
[src:data-formats/yaml] YAML makes this easy, since this simply requires splitting on the document end marker, which is defined as three periods at the start of a line followed by a whitespace (and possible a comment).
[src:data-formats/yaml] In static, compiled languages, this instantiation is complex to achieve and is quite often not implemented.
[src:data-formats/yaml] The perceived flaws and complexity of YAML has led to the emergence of stricter alternatives such as StrictYAML and NestedText.
